title: Mystery of Subhas Chandra Bose's Death | Gumnami Baba | Dhruv Rathee
description:
In this video, we delve into the intriguing mystery surrounding the death of Subhas Chandra Bose, a key figure in India's fight for independence. After Japan's surrender in World War 2, Bose planned a secretive journey to the USSR, departing from Bangkok. Facing logistical challenges in war-torn Asia, his route included a complex flight plan with various stops. Tragically, the plane carrying Bose reportedly crashed in Taiwan. While some accounts state Bose perished in this crash, engulfed in flames, others suggest he survived and lived in hiding. The video explores various theories about his fate, including speculation that he was held captive in the USSR or lived incognito in India as 'Gumnami Baba'. This enduring mystery about Bose's death continues to fascinate and provoke debate, with numerous investigations and theories attempting to uncover the truth.

Learn about the remarkable journey of Subhas Chandra Bose in this video by Dhruv Rathee. title: Sad Reality of Uttarkashi Tunnel Rescue | 3D Animation | Dhruv Rathee
description:

In this video, we delve into the harrowing Uttarkashi Tunnel Disaster that struck on November 12, amidst Diwali celebrations. A catastrophic collapse at an under-construction tunnel in Uttarakhand trapped 41 workers, sparking a desperate, multinational rescue mission. Miraculously, after 17 days, the workers were saved, thanks to the relentless efforts of over 200 people. This disaster highlights the precarious state of the Himalayas, already shaken by the earlier Joshimath sinking. We examine the controversial Char Dham highway project at the heart of these calamities, a massive undertaking aimed at connecting holy sites but criticized for its ecological impact. The documentary sheds light on the government's handling of the project, the risks of tunnel construction in the fragile Himalayan region, and the broader implications of such development projects. Join us as we explore the fine line between natural and man-made disasters and the lessons to be learned from the Uttarkashi rescue operation.

title: The Bhopal Gas Leak | Who were Railway Men? | Dhruv Rathee
description:
Unveil the chilling account of the Bhopal gas tragedy that shook the world on December 3, 1984. This eye-opening video exposes the horrifying aftermath of the poisonous gas leak from the Union Carbide plant, engulfing over 40 square kilometers and affecting a staggering 200,000 lives. Delve into the chaos and heart-wrenching stories from Bhopal Junction railway station, where Deputy Station Superintendent Ghulam Dastagir's heroic efforts amidst the confusion stood as a beacon of hope. Witness the harrowing long-term impact on countless lives, including Dastagir's tragic demise in 2003 due to health complications. title: The Truth about Ramayan | Shri Ram | Diwali Special | Dhruv Rathee
description:
In this video, we delve into the authenticity of the Uttarakand in Valmiki Ramayan, presenting compelling evidence suggesting it may be a later addition. We analyze the concluding chapters of the original text, highlighting how they describe a "happily ever after" scenario in Ram Rajya, which seems inconsistent with the subsequent events in Uttarakand. This provides a strong argument against the inclusion of Uttarakand in the original scripture. Furthermore, the video discusses how the sacred name of "Jai Shree Ram" is being misused today by certain extremist elements to incite violence and hatred. We draw parallels between the misuse of religious chants in various faiths and call for a peaceful reclamation of the name of Lord Ram from those who tarnish it. Join Dhruv Rathee in a thought-provoking exploration of ancient scripture and its relevance in the context of today's world.

title: Why British Left India? | Reality of Mahatma Gandhi's Role | Quit India Movement | Dhruv Rathee
description:
On August 8, 1942, Mahatma Gandhi and the All India Congress Committee gathered at Gowalia Tank Maidan in Mumbai. They came together to advance the fight for independence and find a way to unite the people in this struggle. In his historic speech, Gandhi Ji delivered a simple yet powerful mantra: "Do or Die.” This marked the beginning of the Quit India Movement, a movement that didn't rely on prominent leaders but inspired people to join the fight for freedom. The British authorities, sensing the growing resistance, arrested many leaders, including Gandhi Ji. However, the movement continued to gain momentum, and its impact was so significant that it became one of the most serious rebellions against British rule. In this video, we will explore the inspiring story of how our ancestors united to fight for India's independence during the Quit India Movement, despite facing challenges and arrests. Join Dhruv Rathee in this video to learn more about this remarkable chapter in our history.

title: The Mona Lisa Mystery | Why is it World's Most Famous Painting? | Dhruv Rathee
description:
In this video, Dhruv Rathee dives deep into the captivating tale of the Mona Lisa. Set in the bustling city of Paris, an audacious theft occurs at the Louvre Museum. The mastermind, Vincenzo Peruggia, along with accomplices Michele Lancelotti and Vincenzo, manage to steal Leonardo da Vinci's iconic painting, the Mona Lisa. Astonishingly, the theft has remained unnoticed for nearly 30 hours. Eventually, the world is alerted to the crime, and even the legendary artist Pablo Picasso is questioned! The painting remains missing for 16 months, and its return to the Louvre only adds to its global fame. We then delve into the woman's identity depicted in the painting, Lisa Gherardini, and the various theories surrounding her. The painting's artistic traits, the science behind Mona Lisa's elusive smile, and the discovery of another possible version of the painting are also discussed. Join us as we unravel the mysteries behind one of the world's most celebrated artworks and its intriguing history.

Get real-life skills to create a remarkable impact in software development and data science, Check Out:
https://www.scaler.com/?utm_source=brandedcontent&utm_medium=DhruvratheeDec&utm_campaign=brand_scaler_academy_brandedcontent_DhruvratheeDec_branded-content-video-campaign-DhruvratheeDec-08December2022_india_all&utm_content=YT-description

Aamir Khan's 3 idiots was a superhit movie back then in 2009. We all loved it, but it seems that the message is still not implemented. Because even today in 2022, the pressure on students to pursue stereotypical degrees like engineering, doctor, etc. is real. A kid has to convince his parents to allow him to do something like becoming a YouTuber, Graphic Designer, Video Editor, etc. But why the situation is like this? Why do we have such strong stereotypes? Watch this video by Dhruv Rathee as he explains the root cause of this unfortunate problem that continues to exist in our society for decades - the education system.

Across India, Narendra Modi remains a popular figure, captivating many voters. From Maharashtra's farmers who know Modi's name but not his party, to Uttar Pradesh's elderly struggling with government bureaucracy, and a Mumbai security guard barely making ends meet, the support for Modi is strong and widespread. ****** 
Three major brands have recently found themselves in controversy over the products they have been selling. A report found that Nestle has been adding sugar to its products for babies - and following a double standard because no sugar was found in the same products sold in Western countries like the UK. On the other hand, Hong Kong and Singapore have withdrawn spices from two Indian brands- MDH and EVEREST - because a pesticide called ethylene oxide was found in them. title: How Patanjali Fooled India | Coronil vs Supreme Court
description:
Check out Odoo's eCommerce app here: https://www.odoo.com/r/eE4

****** 

On 10th April 2024, the SC shouted at the Uttarakhand government authorities, "We will rip you apart", for their lack of action against Patanjali when it produced misleading ads for the consumers. Some people were happy that the Govt and Patanjali were finally being shown their place for how its ads fooled Indians. But others like Arnab Goswami immediately asked why the SC is shouting at Patanjali so much and not other FMCG brands like Pepsi, who also show misleading ads. What those people don't realise is that of course we should also criticise every company. However, the strictest punishment should be reserved for those who, during India's toughest medical crisis where, claim that their Ayurvedic medicine can cure people from COVID-19. This is a detailed video about how our government and media supported Patanjali's Coronil when India needed the most scientific solutions.

Astrotalk, an astrology startup swimming in a sea of failed ventures, somehow stays afloat. Offering free horoscopes and relationship pondering, it lures users into paid one-on-one sessions, live chats, and an "Astromall". Its success taps into India's digital natives seeking cosmic guidance amid uncertainties. While critics frown upon its therapy-esque approach, Astrotalk manages to ride the cosmic wave. But even in such a tough economic environment, how is this startup minting crores of profit? That's what this video is about.

Indian Film Industry means glamour but are you aware of its not-so-glamourous side? Have you ever wondered why so many movies fail despite big stars? In this video, we discuss how the Indian Film Industry's glitz meets some real challenges as we uncover why actors' paychecks are causing a stir, making the already tricky movie business even more complicated. But are actors' high fees the REAL problem? From remakes and poorly-written scripts to disastrous VFX, this video uncovers shocking realities behind your favourite blockbusters and also those big-budgeted movies that brought about a much bigger disappointment.

Punjab has been handled, or more like mishandled by many governments until today. 
Once India's second-richest state during the Green Revolution, today Punjab has become a current debt-ridden one. But how did it get here?
In this video we unfold the intricate details of Punjab's financial woes, its overdependence on subsidies, and how political decisions have contributed to the state's fiscal challenges. With insights into the recent actions taken by the AAP government, you'll gain a comprehensive understanding of the state's economic situation and its uncertain future. But the question is, will Punjab be able to ever reclaim its former glory?

In India, there is a widespread perception that everyone is pursuing engineering or medicine. However, a recent study by the Ministry of Education revealed that the most sought-after course is not engineering or medicine but rather Bachelor of Arts (BA). Despite its popularity, BA courses in India face numerous challenges related to employability, the quality of education, and even discrimination from families and employers. In this video, we aim to address the contradiction between the popularity of the BA course and its subpar quality.

On May 18th, 1974, India did something that sent ripples all over the world- we conducted our first nuclear test. This decision was not an easy one- there was a lot of build-up, debates and discussions leading up to this moment. After the test was conducted, India displayed to the world that it too was capable of using nuclear energy. There was one man who needs to be credited greatly for this achievement: Dr. Homi Jehangir Bhabha. A young boy who had set out to study engineering at the University of Cambridge went on to develop India's nuclear program! How did that happen? In this video, we retrace the story that led India to become a nuclear power in the world today.

Kerala has been in the news this year- mostly because of the Kerala story. Based on this movie, Kerala was subject to a lot of criticism. Some said that Kerala is poised to become an Islamic state and something needs to be done about it. Yet there are people who maintain that Kerala is different from other states - That Kerala is truly the most "secular" state in India. So, what is the real Kerala story? 
In this video, we dive into the history of Kerala and the relationship between the communities that exist there. We take a look at the local customs, traditions, and festivals and try to analyze how Kerala has been different from the other states, particularly in the north of India- when it comes to communal harmony. 
But, that being said, Kerala is not totally free from communal violence- there have been cases of communal violence here as well. We take a look at what’s changing in the state and what could possibly be the reason behind this

India has launched the Chandrayaan 3 and the Western nations have all been applauding India for its tremendous achievements in space exploration. But this was not the case back in 1947. When India had become a free country, we were plagued by a plethora of problems- hunger, poverty, and the humungous task of running a nation. In that scenario, thinking of a space program was too ambitious. Even when ISRO was established, the West expressed its doubts over how successful we'd be. But we've beaten all the odds- today, India is set to transform the space and we have a new player on the horizon- the private sector. India has become home to several startups that are attracting investors like Google! In this video, we go through the space journey of India and also discuss what private players have to offer in the field of space.

On June 23rd, a group of soldiers representing the Wagner group rebelled against the Russian military. The private military group’s leader, Yevgeny Prigozhin, said it was a march against Russian military leadership. Just when it seemed that the rebellion could push Russia into an internal armed conflict, Prigozhin suddenly announced that his group was withdrawing from the rebellion. It appeared that Putin had struck a deal with Prigozhin to end the rebellion. What was this bizarre sequence of events? How did a supposed “coup” begin and finish within 24 hours? Who even is Prigozhin and the Wagner group? What impact would the rebellion have on the Ukraine-Russia war, but perhaps more importantly, what could it mean for Putin’s future and his relationship with global powers, including India? These are the things we address in this video.

Shockingly, a survey found that 43% of Indians frequently experience loneliness, ranking India third globally. And research shows that extreme forms of loneliness can lead to depression. But why are more Indians lonely today and what can each one of us to combat it? That is what we shall find out in this video. 
Loneliness affects countless individuals, and it's crucial to understand that help is available. If you or someone you know is struggling with loneliness, seek help and support to combat this significant mental health challenge. You are not alone; help is available.

****** 
India has recently become the most populous country in the world. This means that one thing that we have enough of is population. But despite this, the state government of Sikkim is providing incentives to the people in its state- to encourage them to have more babies. Why is that? This is because the Total fertility rate of Sikkim has fallen to 1.1 which means that on average, a woman in Sikkim is giving birth to only one baby in her reproductive lifespan. This has got the government really worried because a TFR of at least 2.1 is necessary to replace the population at its existing level. A TFR of 1.1 would mean that if things continue the way they are right now, the population of Sikkimese people will be in danger. How dangerous this exactly is and what is the government doing to address that? This is what we will be talking about in this video

On 2 June 2023, tragedy struck when three trains collided near Balasore, Odisha. Two passenger trains, the Coromandel Express and the SMVT Bengaluru–Howrah SF Express, collided after an initial collision involving goods train near Bahanaga Bazar station. At least 275 people were killed and more than a thousand people were injured. In this video, we examine what happened in Odisha, and why it happened. We also discuss the indigenous Kavach system as well as assess the IR, CAG, and NCRB reports to understand what's really wrong with the Indian Railways. Finally, we try to find solutions to avoid such national disasters in the future.

In this video, we talk about why the divorce rates in India are so low- one of the main reasons being the stigma against the idea of divorce. We also talk about how slowly but surely, the stigma is fading and more and more people are choosing to walk out of unhappy and abusive marriages- addressing the reasons behind such decisions as well. 
While making this video, we interviewed a couple of people for their opinions and experience about divorces in India and we'd like to thank them for their contribution. Both of them run support groups-Their details are mentioned below in case you want to reach out to them:

Founding Member - Puruhotra (@puruhotra),
Member - SIF Karnataka (@SIFKtka) / SIF Movement 
Men's Rights Organisation, 
NGO to voice the Human Rights of men. Runs a helpline for men and their families ( 08882 498 498 )

The Arabian society of the past was predominantly organized along tribal lines, with tribes like the Quraysh holding significant influence and power, while others like the Khazraj faced lower social standing. It was within this dynamic atmosphere that Prophet Muhammad, himself from the influential Quraysh tribe, began spreading the message of Islam, emphasizing the equality of all individuals in the eyes of God.
However, it is intriguing to note that, similar to Hindu society, a form of caste system has emerged within the Muslim community in India. In this video, we will delve into the origins and development of caste discrimination among Indian Muslims, seeking a deeper understanding of how and why this phenomenon came to be.

During the 1980s, mainstream Hindi movies were going through a tough time. The decade was most often referred to as the “lost decade” and is remembered for its “trashy” content. Some commentators have called this a “blot” on the history of Indian cinema. 

But during the same decade, a parallel movement was brewing and a new kind of cinema emerged- often referred to as B-Grade movies. These movies had an important influence on mainstream movies by introducing genres like horror and sex. 

In this video, we trace the journey of B-grade movies from its rise in the 1980s, its evolution in the 1990s and its fall in the 2000s, and its rise again in the form of OTT.

Description: Country A and Country B share a border and unfortunately, Country B suffers a defeat in a war against Country A. As a response, Country B seeks to establish a separatist group with the aim of challenging Country A. This scenario may bring to mind the historical context of India and Pakistan, where Pakistan has been known to support and train separatist groups against India. However, it is noteworthy that India, too, has been involved in supporting and training separatist groups in its neighboring countries.

In this video, we delve into the complex dynamics of India's involvement in supporting separatist groups in China, Myanmar, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, and Bangladesh. Moreover, we explore how this particular foreign policy approach can occasionally lead to unintended consequences and may not necessarily prove to be an effective tool in the long run.

Manipur has been on the boil these days- cars have been torched, people have lost their lives, a curfew has been imposed and the army has been brought in. All because of a High Court order- to consider the plea of the Meitei community in Manipur to be included in the Scheduled Tribes of India. But the issue is not a new one. The Meiteis have long been demanding to be declared as STs and the other tribes of the state- the Nagas and the Kukus are determined to not let that happen. 
Why is that? Why do the Meiteis want the ST tag and why are the other tribes so dead against it?
In this video, we delve into history to find the roots of this conflict and also talk about how this has impacted the daily lives of the people in Manipur.

Netaji Subhas Chandra Bose's death has been one of the biggest mysteries of modern India. Nearly eight decades after his disappearance in 1945, people still don't agree about what happened to him. While initial government investigations concluded that Netaji died in a plane crash in present-day Taipei, many saw loopholes in this account and provided alternate theories. One theory states that he somehow managed to make his way to the Soviet Union, where he was captured by Joseph Stalin's forces. Yet another theory says that Netaji didn't die until much later and lived as an ascetic in various parts of India. What really happened and how do we solve this mystery? We examine the evidence available for each theory and reach our own conclusion.

Muhammed Ali Jinnah said "you are free to go to your temples, you are free to go to your mosques or to any other place of worship in this State of Pakistan. You may belong to any religion or caste or creed – that has nothing to do with the business of the state.”
However, the reality for religious minorities in Pakistan today is far from ideal, with instances of forced conversions, discrimination, and violence being reported. This is a complex and deeply concerning issue that demands attention and action. What does this tell about the place of Hindus and minorities in Pakistani society? title: Reality of Indian Startups
description:
India is often referred to as a land of startups and unicorns. A lot of Indian startups have even managed to raise crores of investment from investors. 
But then, there is a flip side to this story as well- More and more startups in India can be seen laying off their employees and they are struggling to survive.
A study even showed that around 90% of Indian startups fail within the first 5 years. 
But why is that? If India has such a huge market of around- 140 crore people and investors have so much faith in Indian startups, why are they struggling to survive?
This is what we are going to talk about in this video What ails the startups of India and what is the way out for them?

The state of Haryana is a picture of contrasts- on one hand, it is counted among the states having the highest per capita income. On the other hand, it suffers such a massive problem of unemployment that it has had the highest rates of unemployment in the country at least 30 times- if you observe the monthly data from 2016. 
The contrast is clear: Haryana is rich but at the same time, a lot of people in Haryana are unemployed.
So, what are the reasons behind this?
This is exactly what we will try and understand in this video: tracing Haryana's history to becoming the richest state in India and then talking about why it faces such a high level of unemployment

As we all saw, UP mafia don turned politician Atiq Ahmed and his brother Ashraf were gunned down on live television. The news immediately prompted severe, polarizing reactions, not only from India but everywhere else too. While many celebrated the death of a dreaded criminal who had been responsible for a reign of terror in Uttar Pradesh for four decades, others saw the killing as a complete breakdown of law and order. When I conducted a poll on my YouTube community page, the responses were equally divisive. So, I began to wonder why some people celebrated, while others thought Ahmed's killing set a dangerous precedent for our democracy. My friend ButWhy and I got together, and we tried to analyze the arguments both for and against the killing and reach our own conclusion. 

Subscribe to @ButWhy

title: Why Haryanvi Songs are Dominating YouTube
description:
Did you know that after Hindi and Punjabi, Haryanvi is the most popular language for songs on YouTube in India? In fact, out of the top 100 most viewed songs from India, Haryana alone has 12 songs on the list. The rise of Haryanvi music can be attributed to several factors, including the regional appeal and relatability of the artists, the performance of Haryanvi athletes at international sporting events, and smartphone accessibility. With catchy beats, foot-tapping rhythms, and vibrant visuals, Haryanvi songs are highly shareable and enjoyable, making them a hit with audiences across India and beyond. Until a few years ago, not a single Haryanvi song made it to the top 10 on YouTube. However, with the rise of social media and the growing demand for regional content, Haryanvi music has emerged as a force to be reckoned with, challenging the dominance of Hindi and Punjabi in the Indian music industry.

title: Truth about Bageshwar Dham Baba
description:
We have a new spiritual guru and guide on the block: Baba Bageshwar Dham. He is like any other babas: he claims he can heal people and gives them strange, quick solutions to people’s problems
He is even known to read people’s minds and offer them a way out of their miseries without the people even telling him anything.
One organization from Maharashtra decided to challenge this. They asked the baba to perform the miracle of mind reading on 10 people of their choice. What the Baba did was pretty predictable. He cut short his visit to Maharashtra and ran away
He was also in news for not allowing a person from a lower caste to touch his feet 
But despite such problematic streaks, the baba is still very popular among the people. The same could be seen in the cases of earlier babas like Ram Rahim and Asaram Bapu
So, why is it that Indians regularly flock to these babas- and they don’t seem to care about their wrongdoings?
This is what we talk about in this video. We also touch upon why such blind belief is problematic and what we could do to address this problem.

title: Why are Punjabis Decreasing in Indian Army?
description:
Over the years, Punjabis, particularly Sikhs have formed a major part of the Indian army. But did you know that they were present in even larger numbers in the British Indian army? Earlier, the British mainly had upper-caste Hindus and Muslims in their army- but then came the revolt of 1857. And that changed the status quo. More and more Punjabis (majorly Sikhs) began to be recruited in the British Indian Army. The dominance of Punjabis and Sikhs in the army continued even after independence- though somewhat in a milder form. But recently, these numbers have been declining. So much so that Punjab, which used to send the highest number of officers and recruits in the army- has been overtaken by other states. 
What could be the reasons behind this? In this video, we talk about what are the major reasons why Punjabis and Sikhs were recruited into the army in such large numbers and then go on to discuss what are the reasons for the decline in this trend.

title: Gay Marriage in India
description:
The Supreme Court of India is currently deliberating on a case that could change the course of history for crores of people. The case, which seeks to legalize same-sex marriages in the country, is being hailed as a "seminal issue", and it's clear why. The petitioners argue that denying same-sex couples the right to marry is a violation of their fundamental human rights and dignity. On the other hand, the government believes that legalizing such marriages could lead to a breakdown in societal values. This debate raises important questions about our society and what we stand for. Should everyone have the right to marry the person they love, regardless of their gender? Should we prioritize societal values over human rights and dignity? These are questions that we try to answer in this video.

title: Pakistan's Economic Crisis
description:
Pakistan, as we know, is facing an unprecedented economic crisis. The prices of food have sky rocketed, malls and offices are being shut down and people are being advised to drink less tea so that the government can save money! Some people are even saying that India should help Pakistan out. 
In the midst of all of this, the Pakistani PM has called for making peace with India. 
He says that after three wars, Pakistan has learnt its lesson. 
But this is not the first time Pakistan has been talking about peace. Several attempts to establish peace have been made in the past.
But peace has been elusive so far.
So, could this time be different? Should India help Pakistan? Would that buy us peace in return?
This is what we are going to talk about in this video. We also discuss why our previous attempts of peace with Pakistan have failed and why this time the situation could be different, if India decides to help at all.

title: Creepy Indian Men
description:
You must have seen videos of a Japanese tourist being troubled by a group of Indian men during Holi celebrations in Delhi. It’s not just the tourists – such behaviour by Indian men is pretty common when it comes to women. And it’s not limited to the physical world; you can find plenty of creepy Indian men online. So, why is it that Indian men are so creepy? Are they really to blame or are there more complex issues at work? Can we really blame a nation of more than 70 crore men for the actions of a few? We delve into what might seem like an amusing problem – but is actually a profound one – in this video.

title: North vs South India on Taxes
description:
We all know that the Central Indian government redistributes the taxes that it receives from the different states. But while some states in the North - like Bihar - receive a lot more than they pay as direct tax to the Centre, others such as Tamil Nadu receive far lesser. This has led many South Indians with a sense of resentment against the Northern states, with the argument being that the Central government is actively discriminating against them. This argument is strengthened when you see the recommendations of the 15th Finance Commission, the body that regulates how much money is to be given to states. But the Northern states argue that historical policies have given the South an advantage. We dive into the complex history and policies behind this issue to determine who is truly right in the latest video.

title: What is Wrong with Indian Liberals
description:
We often see the hardcore Modi supporters or the "right wing" populace being attacked in liberal circles. They are made fun of, ridiculed and even shamed for not being "open" enough to see reason. But have you ever wondered that the liberals might be doing the same thing? For instance, many of those people that identify themselves as "liberals" have chosen to cut off friends that are Modi supporters. Why is that? Is it not okay to have an opinion that is different? And more importantly, if you're not even willing to give the other person the space to voice their opinions or to entertain their ideas, are you even a liberal? This is precisely what we will address in today's video- the problems with some liberals today. We will also try and understand what shapes the ideologies of people and what makes them "liberal" or "conservative" while also seeing why the existence of both these sections is important for the society to exist.

title: Being Single in India
description:
For years and years, the institution of marriage has been very important in Indian society. But in recent years, there’s a different trend that is being noticed- there has been a rise in the number of people who are opting to remain single. The reasons are many- some like the freedom that comes with it, some have decided to wait until they find the right person, no matter how long it takes and some have decided to stay single after a bad experience with a partner/spouse. 
But Being single in India Sucks! 
Singles are being discriminated against in all spheres- “Bachelors/Spinsters are not allowed” is something we very commonly see in housing societies
In this video, we discuss these forms of discrimination faced by single people and try to understand what drives the society to discriminate against them in this way.

title: Khalistan Movement in Punjab
description:
There is a new leader emerging in the turf of Punjab- Amritpal Singh Sandhu. A few years ago, he was an unknown figure who was living in Dubai- today, he is calling for social and religious transformation of Punjab. 
At the same time, he is also talking about Khalistan: a separate homeland for the Sikhs.  His story sounds strikingly similar to a young leader who had emerged in the 1980s- Jarnail Singh Bhindranwale. He had been calling for the transformation of Punjab and raising demands for Khalistan. 
The worrisome thing is- last time, things ended in a very ugly manner. 
Naturally, Indian leaders are worried - what does Amritpal Singh want? Why did he become so popular suddenly? And what does the future hold for Punjab? 
These are the questions we ponder about in this video.

title: Reality of Aurangzeb
description:
How did Mughal Emperor Aurangzeb's actions shape his legacy? Was he a ruthless tyrant, a religious zealot, or a political opportunist? These questions have been the subject of debate for centuries, and continue to be so today. In fact, Aurangzeb's legacy has become increasingly politicized in contemporary India, with his reputation being challenged by the country's Hindu right-wing.Despite his controversial reputation for persecution of Hindus, historians suggest that Aurangzeb's political ambitions were not specifically targeted at any religious group. In this video, we delve into Aurangzeb's life, reign, and legacy, exploring the contradictions and controversies that surround him.

title: Lithium in Jammu and Kashmir: India Next Superpower?
description:
India has made a significant discovery of lithium deposits in Jammu and Kashmir, which makes it one of the largest lithium deposit holders in the world. Lithium, also known as "white gold", is a critical component in rechargeable batteries, particularly for electric vehicles. As the electric vehicle industry is expected to grow 7x by 2030, this discovery provides India with the opportunity to move up the global supply chain and become a leader in the EV industry. Despite the challenges, such as the absence of cell manufacturing in India and the possibility of lithium batteries being replaced in EVs, India has the potential to exploit its natural resources and become a hub for EV production. Will the discovery prove a turning point? Will this make India the next superpower?

title: Adani vs Hindenburg
description:
Gautam Adani's business empire defied naysayers by becoming the largest conglomerate in modern India within a short period of time. Spanning from coal-power to renewable energy, infrastructure to transmission, there is hardly anything left untouched by the Adani Group of industries. But the empire's growth story suffered its biggest blow yet with the publishing of the Hindenburg report, that alleged that Adani had pulled off the biggest con in corporate history. It raised serious allegations about financial fraud and stock manipulation, resulting in the single-biggest erosion in Adani stocks. But Adani claims the report is a result of a malicious attempt to defame not only the company, but India. Whatever the truth, Adani's investors are already sitting on the precipice of disaster. What next?

title: The Secret of India’s Nuclear Policy
description:
🇮🇳 Republic Day Offer 🇮🇳
Get 60% OFF on Kukufm’s 1st Month subscription!!
Only at Rs 39 instead of Rs 99 💥
Use my code FREEDOM60

Link - https://kukufm.sng.link/Apksi/bw9n/wwmx

We all know that India and Pakistan are both nuclear nations, but have you ever wondered about the nuclear policies of the two countries? A country's nuclear policy is important because it dictates how it plans to use the weapons in case of a war. While India has maintained a "no first use" policy for decades - meaning it won't ever use nuclear weapons first - Pakistan hasn't made any such promises. Why? Shouldn't it concern India that in the event of a war, there are no guarantees that Pakistan won't use nuclear weapons first? We anaylze India's position on the use of its nuclear weapons, but even more importantly, we discuss the growing calls by experts to change India's nuclear policy because it's not Pakistan we need to be worried about now - but China! Watch the video to find out more.

title: Are Indian weddings a waste of money?
description:
Take the free hair test:
https://trayahealth.com/MohakMangal
And use my code MM20 to get 20% off on your purchase

****** 
Weddings are, more often than not, a reason for a huge celebration. In India, we take weddings very seriously! Lengthy guest lists, themed decorations, loud bands and a sumptuous food spread- we have it all! But all that comes at a huge cost- A report suggests that  60% of Indian famillies spend more than their annual income on expenditures at a wedding! Which then brings us to our main question- Why do Indians spend so much on weddings? Those that are in favour of lavish weddings would say the reason is obvious- its a once in a lifetime event- we all need to celebrate our big day. But there are others who believe that it is a waste of money- that it is not okay to spend so much on just one celebration. In this video, we discuss the lavish Indian wedding celebrations, with a peek into the past. We even try and look into both the positive and the negative aspects of such spendings.

title: Truth About IIT: Are IITs worth it?
description:
******
#upskillforsuccess #odinschool

******
"Mera beta IITian banega" is a phrase you often hear in Indian households. The dream of becoming an IITian is ingrained in the minds of many Indian students and their families. The IIT brand is seen as a beacon of hope, a ticket to upward mobility and social status. Students spend years pouring over textbooks, sacrificing their social lives, and attending coaching centers in pursuit of this dream. But do the Indian Institutes of Technology truly deliver on these aspirations? Are they really that different from other engineering colleges in India?

In this video, we take a closer look at the quality of IITs and explore whether the "IIT brand" is just hype or if it can truly be justified. We'll dive into the facts and figures, and ask the question on everyone's mind - is the IIT dream worth the sacrifices?

title: Why are Indian men NOT marrying?
description:

#Scaler #CreateImpact #DataScience

******

There are youth organizations who demand different things from their elected leaders. Some want employment, some want reservation, but now there are youth groups who want wives! Yes, a lot of men in India - especially in states like Haryana - are unable to find wives and therefore aren't getting married. Why is this happening? Is it because women's choices have changed or is it something else? And while not being able to find wives is out of their control, there're also men who are not marrying out of choice. Stats show fewer men are marrying today in India than ten years ago, while the population of eligible bachelors has increased. What is the real reason behind this phenomenon and how is it impacting the lives of men and women across the country? Let's find out.

Do you remember the Bihar toppergate scandal when the state toppers made national news for all the wrong reasons? One year later, another scandal hit Bihar's education system as two in every three students failed to pass the 12th Board exams. While these instances might seem funny from the outside, they are stark examples of everything that is wrong with the education system in Bihar. Ultimately, it's the students whose careers are jeopardized. Bihar's education system is beset by corruption and presided over by what is known as "Bihar's education mafia". title: How Punjabis are being scammed
description:
We all know that more Punjabis are settled abroad than people from any other state. We know about the Punjabi populations in countries like Canada, Australia and the UK. But do you know there is another class of Punjabis who are moving to Europe to create a better future for themselves? These young men and women belong to poor, rural families who move abroad with hopes of financial security. Often times, they take massive loans and debts to facilitate this process. However, this migration has a very dark side and it's young Punjabi people and families who are suffering because of it. What is it exactly and how does it work? Let's find out in the video.

description:

(Coupon valid for first 250 users)

****** 

India has been a hub of kidney rackets for a long time. A decade ago, it was estimated that a fifth of the illegal kidney transplants in the world took place in India. These rackets are very elaborate and organised. The organisers of these rackets live lavish lifestyles while the poor who are usually targeted for donations are exploited the most. The reason why these rackets exist is because there is a huge shortfall of organ donations in India due to religious and emotional reasons. Because of this shortage patients have to rely on black market operations. But these could be eliminated if organ donations increase.

Link to sign up for organ donation: https://notto.gov.in/index.htm

You might have seen our recent video on the Pakistani economy. In the video, we discussed the various reasons that for the crisis in Pakistani economy. ****** 

We all know the prestige Indians attach to government jobs. Not only IAS and IPS, even low-ranking government jobs are highly coveted by Indians. How is it that even 30 years after liberalization the Indian youth still prefers the government sector over the private sector? We discuss the reasons behind this obsession which is more complicated than you might think. But even more importantly, we dissect the consequences of this fascination Indians have with government jobs, and show that it's not only harmful for the aspirants, but for the country as well. Wondering how? Watch the video to find out.

#SCALER #CREATEIMPACT

****** 

Until the 1920s, two of the oldest civilizations known to the world were the civilizations of Egypt and Mesopotamia. But all that changed when officers of the Archaeological Survey of India found evidence of an ancient civilization along the banks of the Indus river. The Indus Valley Civilization was home to one of the ancient world's most developed societies. But we still don't know what language the people of this civilization spoke. It remains one of the most enduring mysteries of our time. But today, researchers are using AI to help us decode the Indus script. In this video, we discuss the reasons why deciphering the script has eluded the best of us, and whether we can are any closer to decoding it than we were a hundred years ago.

In 1995, India was brought to a standstill when a Ganesha idol in New Delhi started drinking milk. Within a few hours, it was reported that Ganesha idols not only up and down the country, but even in foreign countries like the US and UK had started drinking milk. What was causing this strange phenomenon? Experts tried to show that there was a simple scientific explanation behind the miracle, and yet people thronged to temples, skyrocketing the price of milk on that day. The crowds included educated people in urban areas, so how was it that these people believed in the miracle too? Was it orchestrated, or did people actually believe in the miracle of gods drinking milk? Our investigation has shown that it was both, as we'll tell you in this video.

description:

******

In 1994, the Idgah Maidan in Karnataka's Hubli district witnessed a storm of protesters. The protest was led by leaders of  BJP on Independence day who wanted to hoist the Indian flag in the Maidan. Result? Ten of the protesters died in the process as the state government intervened. Cut to 2022, Ganesh Chaturthi is celebrated in the very same maidan without any fuss. 
From 1994 to 2022, a lot has changed in Karnataka. A maidan claimed by a religious sect,  where once hoisting the national flag was impossible has just witnessed a festival of another religion being celebrated in its premise. How did that happen? Be it the inception of Hijab Ban controversy, mandating Bhagwat Gita in school curriculum or banning muslim vendors from temple vicinity; there's a visible rise of Hindutva in the state. But popular beliefs suggest that South India generally repeals religious politics. So why is Karnataka moving towards Hindutva? We answer that in this video

******

title: Why UPI should NOT be FREE?
description:
Checkout the Digital Inclusion smallcase here- https://link.smallcase.com/6aY2DWERhtb

******

We've all used UPI and know how convenient, secure and quick it is. Rightly hailed as one of the best deep-tech innovations to have come out of India in this century, the success of the UPI model has made countries like France and USA study the financial payment system, with some like Nepal even adopting it. But a major reason behind UPI growing by leaps and bounds over the last couple of years has been the government's decision to make it free. It has made UPI the undisputed first-choice for millions of users and retailers across the country. But what if I tell you that UPI shouldn't be free, because in the long-run, making UPI free does the system more harm than good. In this video, we'll find out why UPI shouldn't be free, and if the government was to reverse its decision, what it would mean for users like you and me.

India is full of Munna Bhais. A WHO study says that more than half of the doctors in India are fake. But they are very popular in rural India, this is because there is shortage of doctors in rural India and to a large extent the medical education system is to be blamed. Due to this shortage, these informal doctors help fill the gap in rural healthcare but can also prove to be fatal as we see in the case of Unnao. Some believe that training them is right way to go ahead but institutions like the Indian Medical Council are strictly against it. So, the operations of fake doctors of India remain under question.

Netflix show 'Indian Matchmaking' has once again brought the topic of the "big, fat Indian wedding" to the fore. The institution of marriage is important everywhere, but in India, it's often the most important event of an adult's life. While we know that things like caste and religion play a big role in arranged Indian marriages, there are other less-talked about things that young Indians are actively looking for in their prospective partners. In this video, we look at what those things are, and how and why they affect marriage choices among both Indian women and men. We attempt to draw conclusions about factors that decide Indian marriages based on the data and evidence available to us.

"There is not and never was an India,” were the words spoken by former British civil servant John Strachey in a series of lectures he gave in Cambridge in 1888. title: What is HAPPENING in Pakistan?
description:
You might have heard about the US killing a key member of the Al-Qaeda with a drone strike under the direct orders of President Joe Biden. Now when I tell you that seemingly unrelated incident was actually meant to boost Pakistan’s economy, will you be surprised? But that’s exactly what some experts reckon. Pakistan is going through one of the worst economic crises in their history, with the Pakistani rupee currently the worst-performing currency in Asia. And it needs another IMF financial bailout if it has to survive and not follow in Sri Lanka’s footsteps into economic disaster. How have our neighbours reached this position? We examine if Pakistan’s current situation is a result of recent global developments like the Ukraine-Russia war, or if has been a long time in the making.

description:

******

What goes on in your mind when you see news headlines like these: "Nora Fateh turns up the heat in an animal print bikini" or "Mallaika Arora bra pehne bina ghar se doggy ko tehlaane nikli, tasveerey ho rahi hai viral".  I beleive you resonate our feelings: IS THAT NEWS? But what if I tell you these and such similar headlines appear on the web portals of established media houses like News 18, NDTV and the Times of India all the time.  If you closely observe these articles, there's a pattern; they are similarly worded, they use a lot of explicit images and they are one of the most viewed articles on the news portal. While we might thing such clickbaits are the real problem, they are not. They are one of the consequences of a gradual shift in our media consumption and a broken business model. In this video we discuss how one of the oldest media business models is ruining the news for us.

title: Why is SSR TRENDING?
description:
Link:https://kukufm.sng.link/Apksi/bw9n/wwmx
Code: MOHAK50
Offer valid for first 250 users only.

******

It's been almost two years since Bollywood actor Sushant Singh Rajput passed away. But on Twitter, he still has an afterlife. No one of us can forget the massive outrage and somewhat bizarre media coverage that Sushant' death got. Although, the TV media doesn't discuss his death much but if you look at Twitter, there are thousands of tweets with hashtags containing the word Sushant or SSR. Like in January 2022 #FasttrackJustice4SSR had around 40 thousand tweets. This trended on number 7 in India on January 17th. This is strange because two years after the death of any celebrity, a movement tends to die. So why, is the Why is #SSR movement still going strong? Let's find out in this video

Read the research work by Joyojeet on Sushant Singh Rajput trend here :
http://joyojeet.people.si.umich.edu/ssr/

title: Why was Bombay SPLIT into Maharashtra and Gujarat?
description:
Download Link - https://kukufm.sng.link/Apksi/bw9n/wwmx
Coupon code - MOHAK50
(Coupon valid for first 250 users)

******

The states of Maharashtra and Gujarat were once a single state known as the state of Bombay under the British. Upon independence, there were demands to create separate states of Gujarat and Maharashtra on the basis of language. The centre didn't want this but appointed several commissions to look into this matter. Finally, when protests grew from both the Marathi and Gujarati sides, the centre divided the state of Bombay into Maharashtra and Gujarat on May 1,1960.

title: Why are Indians NOT looking for jobs?
description:

Fast forward your career in Data Science & Analytics with Top Industry Experts at upGrad. 

#FFwithupGrad #upGrad #lifelonglearning 

******

Last year, UP Chief Minister Yogi Adityanath spoke of the declining unemployment figures in his state. He claimed that Uttar Pradesh's unemployment rate has dipped from 17% in 2017 to 5% in 2021. While Adityanath's claim was not faulty, the rationale behind it was. Unemployment rate didn't fall because people got jobs, but because people stopped looking for one. And this phenomenon is not only restricted to Uttar Pradesh. Between 2017 to 2022, 40% of India's working population stopped looking for a job, a figure that equals the combined population of Russia and the U.S. So why is it happening? Watch the video to find out..

A market in Manipur's Imphal houses over 4000 vendors, all of them women. This marketplace is a mini representation of Manipur's society, where women are at the forefront of running the economy. title: India's Communist Freedom Fighter
description:

Coupon code - MOHAK50
(Coupon valid for first 250 users)

******

In 1917, the Mexican communist party was established. The man behind the formation  was not a Mexican, but an Indian. It was MN Roy, a highly motivated communist revolutionary who had escaped to Mexico because of a completely different reason. His endeavours to get India independent took him to different parts of the world, and forming the communist party of mexico, was just one of this endeavour. His loyalty towards communism drew him close to Lenin, who trusted him to seed India's communist party as well. But, the man who led the formation of communist parties in two countries abandoned communism a few years later. In this video we narrate this fascinating story of one of India's first global leaders.

title: Bihar has no industries. Why?
description:
The first 1000 people to use this link will get a 1 month free trial of Skillshare- https://skl.sh/sochbymohakmangal04221

******

In the last twenty years, Bihar has been able to overcome the stereotypical image it was subjected to. Between 2006 and 2011, while the growth rate of other states (in terms of GSDP) was stagnating, Bihar’s GSDP was growing at double the rate it grew in the last 5 years.
But one problem stuck with the state even after this immense growth: be it in the manufacturing sector, or the service sector, Bihar was unable to establish industries. CM Nitish Kumar and other leaders from the state have asserted that Bihar lacks industry because it has no port. But Haryana, Punjab, Madhya Pradesh and Rajasthan, are also landlocked, and still have industries 2 or 3 times more than Bihar. So is it Bihar’s image causing it to lose out on industries? Well partly, but there are other contemporary reasons which are pulling the state down. In this video, we will discuss those very reasons..

The Research and Analysis Wing (RAW) is India's premier intelligence agency, responsible for foreign intelligence gathering, counter-terrorism, and covert operations. Established in 1968, RAW plays a crucial role in ensuring national security and protecting India's interests abroad. Operating under the Cabinet Secretariat, the agency conducts espionage activities, monitors political and military developments in neighboring countries, and combats threats to India’s sovereignty. With its headquarters in New Delhi, RAW has grown into a formidable force, respected and feared globally for its sophisticated intelligence and operational capabilities. Discover more about RAW's intriguing history, missions, and its impact on global intelligence dynamics in this comprehensive overview.

The Nirav Modi scam, one of India's largest financial frauds, unfolded in 2018 when billionaire jeweler Nirav Modi, along with his family and associates, allegedly defrauded Punjab National Bank (PNB) of over $2 billion. Modi and his accomplices purportedly obtained fraudulent letters of undertaking (LoUs) to secure credit from other banks, using these funds for personal gain and to sustain his luxury lifestyle. The scandal rocked India's banking sector, revealing systemic vulnerabilities and prompting widespread scrutiny of regulatory oversight and corporate governance practices.

title: Planning Of Article 370 Removal
description:
Download the TRAYA app now and take the FREE Hair Test:
https://trayahealth.app.link/9Jp1dcakWHb
Use my code 20NR to get 20% off on your purchase.
---------------------------------
Article 370 of the Indian Constitution, originally included as a temporary provision, grants special autonomous status to the region of Jammu and Kashmir. Enacted in 1949, it allows the state to have its own constitution, flag, and governing authority, with the central government's jurisdiction limited to defense, foreign affairs, and communications. Over time, Article 370 has been a subject of controversy, with debates over its effectiveness in maintaining stability in the region versus accusations of perpetuating separatism. Its abrogation in August 2019 by the Indian government sparked both celebration and protest, significantly altering the political landscape of Jammu and Kashmir.

Iran's animosity towards the USA is deeply rooted in historical grievances, notably the controversial 1953 coup that ousted Prime Minister Mossadegh and installed the Shah, widely seen as a U.S.-backed intervention. The 1979 Islamic Revolution, which overthrew the Shah, further strained relations, leading to the hostage crisis. Perceived American interference in Iran's domestic affairs, coupled with accusations of supporting opposition groups and imposing economic sanctions, has fueled a persistent distrust. Geopolitical differences, especially regarding regional conflicts and nuclear policies, continue to contribute to the complex and contentious nature of their relationship. The result is a multifaceted dynamic marked by decades of diplomatic challenges and mutual suspicion.

title: How India Got Its Name?
description:
India vs. Bharat: Nation Identity Debate delves into the intricate and multifaceted conversation surrounding India's dual identity. With its rich history and diverse cultural tapestry, India often grapples with the tension between its urban, technologically advanced facade and its rural, tradition-bound hinterlands. This documentary explores the contrasting narratives of 'India' as a global economic powerhouse and 'Bharat' as the heartland, where age-old customs and agrarian livelihoods continue to thrive. Through insightful interviews, vivid visuals, and thought-provoking commentary, the film unravels the complex web of social, economic, and political factors that contribute to this identity divide.

As the viewer embarks on this cinematic journey, they will gain a deeper understanding of the implications of this identity debate on India's socio-economic landscape. From the challenges of bridging the urban-rural gap to the impact on policy decisions, "India vs. Bharat: Nation Identity Debate" invites viewers to contemplate the intricate interplay between tradition and modernity in one of the world's most diverse and dynamic nations. This thought-provoking documentary sheds light on the complexities of India's dual identity and asks us to question how these two facets can coexist harmoniously in the 21st century.

title: How Social Media Uses Your Data
description:
The reality of social media today is a complex tapestry of connection, influence, and vulnerability. On the one hand, it has revolutionized how we communicate, allowing us to connect with friends and family across the globe, share our passions, and discover new horizons. However, beneath the glossy filters and curated feeds lies a darker side—a world of comparison, addiction, and privacy concerns. Many users grapple with the pressure to project a flawless image, leading to feelings of inadequacy and anxiety. Moreover, the constant barrage of information and the algorithmic echo chambers can skew our perceptions of reality and polarize our beliefs. In this digital age, understanding the nuanced facts of social media is essential to harnessing its benefits while safeguarding our mental well-being and privacy.

Navigating the realities of social media requires a discerning eye and a critical mind. It's a place where authenticity can shine but often competes with carefully constructed personas. Users must be vigilant about the information they consume and share, as misinformation and echo chambers thrive in the digital realm. Privacy concerns demand a closer look at how our data is collected and used, prompting discussions about digital rights and online ethics. In this ever-evolving landscape, fostering a healthy relationship with social media involves striking a balance between staying connected and safeguarding our mental and emotional well-being, ultimately reminding us that the power to shape digital reality lies in our hands.

In recent times, concerns have arisen about the practices of certain segments of Indian media, revealing a pattern of subtle news suppression that has raised eyebrows among both citizens and watchdog organizations. While media is traditionally seen as a pillar of democracy, these concerns suggest a departure from its intended role. Critics argue that a combination of editorial bias, corporate influence, and political pressure has led to the selective coverage of news stories. By strategically underplaying or altogether ignoring certain stories, Indian media outlets may be inadvertently shaping public opinion and limiting citizens' access to a well-rounded understanding of critical events. As media's influence remains profound, an open discourse about news transparency and accountability has become increasingly vital in maintaining a healthy democratic society.

The implications of this alleged silent news suppression are far-reaching. With the rise of digital platforms, the speed at which information spreads has increased exponentially, making the role of media in shaping public perception more crucial than ever. By systematically sidelining certain stories, media outlets might be compromising their responsibility to inform the public objectively. As citizens become more cognizant of these dynamics, demands for greater media integrity, unbiased reporting, and ethical journalism are echoing across the nation, calling for a reevaluation of media practices and a renewed commitment to upholding the principles of a free and transparent press.

title: How Bollywood Movies Earn Money?
description:
Get 75% OFF on Seekho Plus’s Monthly subscription!!
Only at Rs 49 instead of Rs 199 🤑🤑
Use my code NR49!
Click the link ⬇️ https://applinks.seekhoapp.com/jLCwkjsffova4iwr8

---------------------------------
Bollywood movies, like most mainstream films worldwide, generate revenue through multiple streams. One of the primary sources of income for Bollywood movies is box office collections. When a film is released in theaters, audiences purchase tickets to watch it, and a significant portion of the ticket sales goes back to the movie's producers and distributors. Successful films can make substantial profits in this manner. Additionally, the sale of distribution rights, both domestic and international, contributes significantly to a movie's earnings. Bollywood movies are often sold to various platforms, such as streaming services, television networks, and DVD distributors, which allows the producers to monetize their content further. Apart from that, product placements and brand tie-ups serve as additional revenue streams, where companies pay to have their products or brands featured prominently within the film. Merchandising and music rights also play a role in generating income, with soundtracks and movie-related products being sold to fans and enthusiasts.

The success of Bollywood movies is not only confined to the Indian market but extends to the global audience as well. Overseas theatrical releases and international distribution contribute substantially to the box office revenue. In recent years, streaming platforms have gained immense popularity, and Bollywood movies have taken advantage of this trend. Producers strike deals with digital platforms to release their films directly on these services, reaching a vast online audience and generating revenue through subscriptions or pay-per-view models. Additionally, satellite rights, where TV networks pay for the rights to broadcast the movie, are a significant source of income. The combination of these diverse revenue streams and the ever-growing global popularity of Bollywood films has made the industry a lucrative and thriving powerhouse in the entertainment world.

The NCB claimed that they had received a tip-off that a rave party was being held on a cruise ship, the Cordelia, and that drugs were being consumed. They raided the ship and arrested Khan and several others.

Khan was released on bail after spending 22 days in jail. The case is still ongoing, and it is unclear whether he will be convicted.

In recent months, there have been allegations of corruption against Sameer Wankhede, the NCB officer who led the raid on the Cordelia. Wankhede has denied the allegations, but he has been transferred to a different post.

The Cordelia cruise drug case has raised many questions about the NCB's methods and its role in targeting celebrities. It remains to be seen how the case will unfold, but it is clear that it has had a significant impact on Indian society.

title: Why Did Elon Buy Twitter?
description:
Elon Musk acquired Twitter for several reasons, combining his interest in promoting free speech, his critique of the platform's existing content moderation policies, and his vision for transforming it into a more open and inclusive digital town square. Musk, who is known for his ventures in technology and space exploration through companies like Tesla and SpaceX, views Twitter as a crucial platform for public discourse. He has expressed intentions to enhance Twitter's capabilities for free speech while also addressing concerns related to censorship and the platform's role in public debates. Musk's acquisition of Twitter reflects his broader ambitions to influence the global conversation on technology, freedom of expression, and the future of digital communication.
